{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-02-11T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Death Valley National Park challenges first impressions. Spanning more than 1.34 million hectares across California and Nevada in the United States, it is the largest national park in the contiguous United States. Across this vast expanse, salt flats, volcanic hills, sweeping sand dunes and distant snowcapped peaks create a landscape shaped by time and extremes. From the soaring heights of Telescope Peak, which rises over 3,300 metres above the desert floor, to the depths of Badwater Basin, 86 metres below sea level, the park is a study in contrasts.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BadwaterFlats_ROW9539566313_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BadwaterFlats_ROW9539566313_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Salt flats in Badwater Basin, Death Valley National Park, California, USA","Copyright":"© Jim Patterson/TANDEM Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260211_BadwaterFlats\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Death+Valley+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260211_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260211_BadwaterFlats"},"Ssd":"20260211","Name":"BadwaterFlats","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9539566313","FullDateString":"11 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Just southwest of Ibiza, Spain, lie the uninhabited islets of Es Vedrà and Es Vedranell. Part of a protected nature reserve, these dramatic rock formations are admired for their ecological value and visual impact. Es Vedrà rises around 400 metres straight from the sea, its sheer limestone cliffs resembling a mountain range. Nearby, the jagged outline of Es Vedranell has earned it the nickname 'sleeping dragon,' appearing to guard its larger sibling.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.IbizaIslets_ROW9500187441_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.IbizaIslets_ROW9500187441_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Islets of Es Vedrà and Es Vedranell, Ibiza, Spain","Copyright":"© L. Apolli/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260210_IbizaIslets\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Es+Vedra+Ibiza&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260210_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260210_IbizaIslets"},"Ssd":"20260210","Name":"IbizaIslets","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9500187441","FullDateString":"10 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The leopard cat is a small wild cat found across South, Southeast and East Asia. Similar in size to a house cat but longer-legged and slenderer, it generally measures 38–66 centimetres long, with a tail about 17–31 centimetres. Depending on the region, adults weigh roughly 0.55–7 kilograms. Their appearance varies widely: southern individuals tend to have warm golden coats, while those farther north often have pale grey fur that thickens for winter.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LeopardCat_ROW9470593052_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LeopardCat_ROW9470593052_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Amur leopard cat, Russia","Copyright":"© Valeriy Maleev/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260209_LeopardCat\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Leopard+cat&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260209_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260209_LeopardCat"},"Ssd":"20260209","Name":"LeopardCat","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9470593052","FullDateString":"9 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The island of Corfu, Greece, meets you at night with a quiet kind of intensity: stone facades catching warm lamplight, fortress walls rising in sharp outline and narrow lanes unfolding like a lived-in labyrinth. The Old Town doesn't just look historic—it feels inhabited, shaped by centuries of shifting cultures and the slow rhythm of island life after dark.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CorfuGreece_ROW8621582269_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CorfuGreece_ROW8621582269_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Corfu, Greece","Copyright":"© whitewizzard/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260208_CorfuGreece\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Corfu+Greece&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260208_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260208_CorfuGreece"},"Ssd":"20260208","Name":"CorfuGreece","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8621582269","FullDateString":"8 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Salar de Uyuni in Bolivia doesn't ease you in—it erupts into view like a horizon made of light. It's the world's largest salt flat, stretching across more than 10,400 square kilometres at nearly 3,658 metres above sea level. The landscape dramatically shifts with the seasons: when the rain arrives, the surface floods just enough to become an enormous mirror, so perfectly reflective that sky and ground melt into a single glowing plane.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SalarUyuni_ROW9588613912_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SalarUyuni_ROW9588613912_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Salar de Uyuni salt flats in Bolivia","Copyright":"© Abstract Aerial Art/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260207_SalarUyuni\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Salar+de+Uyuni+Bolivia&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260207_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260207_SalarUyuni"},"Ssd":"20260207","Name":"SalarUyuni","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9588613912","FullDateString":"7 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At the Giau Pass, where cyclists gasp and clouds drift like they're sightseeing too, this sharp-backed peak rises with quiet confidence. It's the kind of mountain that says, 'Take your time,' and then steals your breath anyway. Ra Gusela sits above Giau Pass, one of the most scenic high passes in the Dolomites, just outside Cortina d'Ampezzo. At 2,595 metres, it isn't the tallest neighbour in the room, but it has presence.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.GiauPass_ROW8285301958_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.GiauPass_ROW8285301958_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Ra Gusela peak at Giau Pass, near Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy","Copyright":"© Tomasz Podolski/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260206_GiauPass\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Ra+Gusela+peak&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260206_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260206_GiauPass"},"Ssd":"20260206","Name":"GiauPass","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8285301958","FullDateString":"6 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Xwejni Bay in Gozo, Malta, has a way of making everyday elements look like a quiet choreography between sea, stone and sun. You can't help but pause and look closer, right? Centuries back, families began carving these limestone pans, shaping hundreds of basins that trap seawater with each wave. Once the water settles in, the sun's heat does the rest, slowly evaporating it into natural Mediterranean salt. Gozo became a salt-making hub because its limestone coast is easy to shape, and its warm, dry summers keep the crystallisation process steady. The first crystals form around May, marking the beginning of the harvesting season. Workers rake the salt by hand, sweep it with brooms and brushes, gather it into small piles to dry for another day, then bag it and store it in the caves.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.MaltaSalt_ROW3900508445_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.MaltaSalt_ROW3900508445_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Salt evaporation ponds on the island of Gozo, Malta","Copyright":"© Marius Roman/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260205_MaltaSalt\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Gozo+Malta&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260205_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260205_MaltaSalt"},"Ssd":"20260205","Name":"MaltaSalt","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3900508445","FullDateString":"5 Şub, 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"This species missed the domestication memo and kept going on its own terms. Say hello to Przewalski's horse, considered the last truly wild horse on Earth. Once widespread across Central Asia, it disappeared from the wild in the 1960s after decades of hunting, habitat loss and competition with livestock. Its survival depended on an unlikely lifeline: a small number of individuals captured by early 20th‑century collectors, which became the foundation of all modern Przewalski's horses.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PrzewalskisHorse_ROW1038206758_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PrzewalskisHorse_ROW1038206758_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Przewalski's horses","Copyright":"© Nemyrivskyi Viacheslav/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260218_PrzewalskisHorse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Przewalskis+horse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260218_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260218_PrzewalskisHorse"},"Ssd":"20260218","Name":"PrzewalskisHorse","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1038206758","FullDateString":"18 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ochagavía in Spain offers one of Navarre's most evocative winter scenes. This village of just over 480 residents, located in the Salazar Valley, 85 kilometres from Pamplona, stands out for its traditional architecture, with stone houses, steeply pitched roofs and a medieval bridge over the Anduña River that looks straight out of a postcard.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Navarra_ROW0874580487_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Navarra_ROW0874580487_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Ochagavía, Navarre, Spain","Copyright":"© PhotosTime/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260217_Navarra\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Ochagavia&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260217_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260217_Navarra"},"Ssd":"20260217","Name":"Navarra","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0874580487","FullDateString":"17 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Banff in Alberta, Canada, didn't grow quietly. It arrived with railways, hot springs and a vision: to protect places of rare beauty. In 1883, railway workers stumbled upon warm mineral water bubbling from Sulphur Mountain—an unlikely surprise in the cold sweep of the Rockies. The discovery drew attention quickly. By 1885, the surrounding land has been set aside as a protected reserve. What did that lead to? The beginnings of Banff National Park, Canada's first, and a blueprint the country would return to again and again.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BanffWinter_ROW0592236098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BanffWinter_ROW0592236098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Banff, Alberta, Canada","Copyright":"© Herbert Rong/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260216_BanffWinter\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Banff+town&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260216_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260216_BanffWinter"},"Ssd":"20260216","Name":"BanffWinter","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0592236098","FullDateString":"16 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Humpback whales are easily recognisable by their long pectoral fins and are known for their complex songs associated with breeding behaviour. Their predictable migrations bring them close to shore, turning them into both a cultural marker of the season and a focal point for early conservation efforts.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.MontereyHumpbacks_ROW0446556209_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.MontereyHumpbacks_ROW0446556209_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Humpback whales in Monterey Bay, California, USA","Copyright":"© Kiliii Fish/Cavan Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260215_MontereyHumpbacks\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Humpback+whales&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260215_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260215_MontereyHumpbacks"},"Ssd":"20260215","Name":"MontereyHumpbacks","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0446556209","FullDateString":"15 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At first glance, it looks like a love story that went a little too far. Pink hearts dangle from curved stems, each with a tiny white drop at the tip, as if the plant is mid-sigh. Meet the bleeding heart—proof that flowers can be dramatic without saying a word. Formally known as Dicentra spectabilis, it is a spring-flowering perennial native to eastern Asia. It can grow up to 60 centimetres tall and spread to nearly 75 centimetres wide, creating a graceful, almost poetic display.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ValentineHearts_ROW0216813332_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ValentineHearts_ROW0216813332_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Bleeding hearts","Copyright":"© Dorene Hookey/Cavan Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260214_ValentineHearts\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bleeding+hearts&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260214_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260214_ValentineHearts"},"Ssd":"20260214","Name":"ValentineHearts","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0216813332","FullDateString":"14 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Before bridges, rivers set the pace of travel. Now, with bridges, people do. That shift explains why cross-border links like the Third Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge connecting Laos and Thailand matter. Bridges come in many forms, each built to meet a specific challenge. Arch bridges manage compression, suspension bridges span long distances and concrete box-girder bridges prioritise stability and load efficiency. This bridge uses the box-girder design, making it a practical choice for crossing the wide, fast-moving Mekong River.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FriendshipBridge_ROW0019277166_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FriendshipBridge_ROW0019277166_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Third Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge connecting Laos and Thailand","Copyright":"© chaiyut samsuk/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260213_FriendshipBridge\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Third+Thai+Lao+Friendship+Bridge&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260213_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260213_FriendshipBridge"},"Ssd":"20260213","Name":"FriendshipBridge","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0019277166","FullDateString":"13 Şub, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"When romance calls, this bird lifts one bright blue foot, then the other, like it's auditioning for a talent show with very strict colour rules. Not metaphorically. Literally. Meet the blue-footed booby. Widely associated with the Galápagos Islands, these seabirds range across the eastern tropical Pacific.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DarwinBooby_ROW9751594098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DarwinBooby_ROW9751594098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Blue-footed booby, Galápagos Islands, Ecuador","Copyright":"© Karine Aigner/TANDEM Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260212_DarwinBooby\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Blue+footed+b